I&#39;m working on an XSD file for XML files that need to be sent to a legacy system. This legacy system has field size restrictions specified in # of UTF-16 code units.

For example, the field `description` may not contain more than 35 UTF-16 code units.

**I&#39;m now trying to come up with a regular expression that I can put into the XSD so that it restricts the respective field value to contain at most 35 UTF-16 codes units.**

My first attempt was this:

```
	&lt;xs:element name=&quot;description&quot;&gt;
		&lt;xs:annotation&gt;
			&lt;xs:documentation&gt;A description for the document&lt;/xs:documentation&gt;
		&lt;/xs:annotation&gt;
		&lt;xs:simpleType&gt;
			&lt;xs:annotation&gt;
				&lt;xs:documentation&gt;A sequence of up to 35 UTF-16 code units&lt;/xs:documentation&gt;
			&lt;/xs:annotation&gt;
			&lt;xs:restriction base=&quot;xs:string&quot;&gt;
				&lt;xs:pattern value=&quot;^(|([\x{0}-\x{FFFF}][\x{0}-\x{FFFF}]|[\x{10000}-\x{10FFFF}]){0,17}[\x{0}-\x{FFFF}]?|[\x{0}-\x{FFFF}]?([\x{0}-\x{FFFF}][\x{0}-\x{FFFF}]|[\x{10000}-\x{10FFFF}]){0,17})$&quot;/&gt;
			&lt;/xs:restriction&gt;
		&lt;/xs:simpleType&gt;
	&lt;/xs:element&gt;
```

Some background behind this regular expression:

 - A BMP (basic multilingual plane) character (`[\x{0}-\x{FFFF}]`) is represented as a single UTF-16 code unit.
 - An astral plane character (`[\x{10000}-\x{10FFFF}]`) is represented as two UTF-16 code units (as a surrogate pair).

My (failed) idea was to implement this restriction:

- There are at most 17 groups that are either a) a pair of BMP characters, or b) a single astral plane character.
- These at most 17 groups may either be preceded or followed by a single BMP character.

But obviously, this fails for strings like `a&#128512;a&#128512;a` where there is a single BMP character in between two astral plane characters.

Is there maybe another way to implement a restriction for the number of UTF-16 code units in an XSD file?

